      "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 3 (MODERATE): Connection pool exhaustion or DNS resolution delays. HTTP client connection pools to external services may be undersized or leaking. As connections accumulate without being properly returned, new requests queue for available connections. TLS handshake overhead compounds this. DNS TTL changes on external services could also introduce lookup delays.",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Check HTTP client connection pool metrics, socket states (TIME_WAIT accumulation), and DNS resolution times. Verify keep-alive settings and connection reuse."
    },
    {
      "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 4 (MODERATE): Sequential call pattern amplifying tail latency. If all three external APIs are called sequentially, P99 latency = P99(geo) + P99(rates) + P99(payment) + P99(db). Even modest degradation in each (e.g., each going from ~50ms P99 to ~450ms P99) produces 1800ms total. This is a structural amplification problem.",
      "severity": "high",
