      "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 5 (LOW-MODERATE): TLS certificate chain or intermediate CA changes on an external API causing longer handshake times, especially if connections are not being reused.",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Check TLS handshake durations in HTTP client metrics. Verify certificate chain completeness on external APIs. Ensure HTTP keep-alive is functioning."
    },
    {
      "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 6 (LOW): Gradual data growth causing serialization/deserialization overhead. If carrier rate responses are growing (more carriers, more rate tiers), JSON parsing time increases. Unlikely to account for 1600ms increase at 10K req/day volume.",
      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "Profile response payload sizes over the two-week window. Check for response size trends."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Observability blind spot: no per-dependency latency tracking",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "This is the highest-priority fix regardless of root cause. Without per-call timing, the team is flying blind. Add structured logging or metrics for each external call with: service name, endpoint, response time, response size, HTTP status code."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "IMMEDIATE DIAGNOSIS (Day 1): Add per-dependency latency instrumentation around each external API call. This will identify the culprit within hours. Use structured logging with fields: {service, endpoint, duration_ms, status_code, response_size}. IMMEDIATE MITIGATION (Day 1-2): Add aggressive timeouts to all external calls — 500ms connect, 1000ms read. Add a circuit breaker per external service (half-open after 30s, trip after 5 consecutive timeouts). SHORT-TERM FIX (Week 1): Cache geocoding results aggressively (addresses → coordinates are essentially immutable, TTL of 30 days is safe). Cache carrier rates with a short TTL (5-15 minutes). Parallelize geocoding and carrier rate lookups — they are independent. MEDIUM-TERM (Week 2-3): Implement proper observability with percentile-based latency dashboards per external dependency. Add alerting on P95 latency per dependency exceeding 300ms. Consider a fallback rate cache that serves stale rates when the carrier API is slow (stale rates > no rates).",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "Add middleware/interceptor for HTTP client timing instrumentation",
      "Add timeout configuration per external service",
      "Add circuit breaker wrapper (e.g., resilience4j, opossum, polly depending on language)",
      "Add caching layer for geocoding responses",
      "Add caching layer for carrier rate responses with short TTL",
      "Refactor call orchestration to parallelize independent external calls"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Circuit Breaker pattern for external call resilience. Bulkhead pattern to isolate external dependency failures. Cache-Aside pattern for geocoding and rate lookups. Parallel Scatter-Gather for independent external calls. Structured observability with per-dependency dashboards.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT add retries without timeouts — retries on slow (not failing) services will make things worse by multiplying load",
      "Do NOT set a single global timeout — each external service has different latency profiles and needs individual timeout tuning",
      "Do NOT cache payment gateway responses — these are transactional and must be live",
      "Do NOT blame the database without evidence — dashboard shows it is healthy, and this is a classic misdirection when the real issue is external API latency",
      "Do NOT add aggressive retry logic before understanding which service is slow — retrying a slow geocoding service 3x turns a 600ms call into 1800ms"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "The root cause is external API latency, not database or internal processing — the evidence strongly supports this",
      "The system lacks per-dependency observability — this is definitionally true given the team cannot identify which external call is slow",
      "Sequential external calls amplify tail latency — this is a mathematical certainty given the architecture",
      "Caching geocoding results would provide significant and safe latency reduction"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Which specific external API is the primary culprit — requires instrumentation to confirm",
      "Whether caching exists and has degraded, vs. never existing — requires codebase inspection",
      "Whether calls are truly sequential or already parallelized — requires codebase inspection",
      "Whether connection pool issues are contributing — requires runtime metrics"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "External API calls are made synchronously and sequentially during request processing",
      "No caching layer exists for geocoding or carrier rate results (or it has degraded)",
      "The dashboard showing normal DB times is accurate and covers the relevant queries",
      "The 10K requests/day figure means this is NOT a throughput/load problem — it is a per-request latency problem",
      "No infrastructure changes (network, DNS, firewall, proxy) occurred in the two-week window"
    ]
  }
}

